# Contributing to {{PROJECT_NAME}}

Thank you for your interest in contributing to {{PROJECT_NAME}}! This document outlines the guidelines and processes for contributing to our project.

## Getting Started

1. **Fork the repository** and clone it locally
2. **Set up your development environment** following our [setup guide](../documentation/guides/getting-started.md)
3. **Read our standards** in the `governance/standards/` directory
4. **Check existing issues** to see what needs work

## Code of Conduct

All contributors must adhere to our [Code of Conduct](code-of-conduct.md). We are committed to providing a welcoming and inclusive environment for everyone.

## How to Contribute

### Reporting Issues
- Use the [issue template](.github/issue_template.md)
- Search existing issues first to avoid duplicates
- Provide clear reproduction steps
- Include relevant system information

### Submitting Changes
1. **Create a feature branch** from `develop`
2. **Make your changes** following our coding standards
3. **Write or update tests** as appropriate
4. **Update documentation** if needed
5. **Submit a pull request** using our [PR template](.github/pull_request_template.md)

### Pull Request Process
- PRs must target the `develop` branch
- All checks must pass (CI, tests, code review)
- Requires at least one approval from a core team member
- Squash commits when merging

## Development Guidelines

### Coding Standards
- Follow our [coding standards](standards/coding-standards.md)
- Use consistent formatting and naming conventions
- Write self-documenting code with clear comments
- Ensure all tests pass

### Testing
- Write unit tests for new functionality
- Maintain test coverage above 80%
- Run tests locally before submitting PR
- Follow our [testing standards](standards/testing-standards.md)

### Documentation
- Update relevant documentation
- Follow our [documentation standards](standards/documentation-standards.md)
- Include code comments for complex logic
- Update API documentation if applicable

## Review Process

1. **Automated checks** run on all PRs
2. **Code review** by at least one team member
3. **Testing** in staging environment if applicable
4. **Final approval** by project maintainer

## Getting Help

- Join our discussions in GitHub Discussions
- Ask questions in issues using the "question" label  
- Review our [FAQ](../documentation/shared-resources/faq.md)
- Contact maintainers directly for sensitive issues

## Recognition

Contributors will be recognized in our [contributors list](CONTRIBUTORS.md) and release notes.

